<TITLE> BNP starts 3-day programmes to mark Zia's death anniversary </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, May 29 (bdnews24.com)The BNP launched a three-day central programme on Friday to observe the 28th death anniversary of its founder late president Ziaur Rahman. The central programme began in the afternoon with a discussion at Institution of Engineers, Bangladesh in the capital. On Saturday morning, national and party will fly at half-mast at the party headquarters at Naya Paltan. The placing of wreath at the graveyard of the late president is set for 10am Saturday which will be followed by destitute feeding at different wards in the city. The anniversary programme will culminate on May 31 with a seminar on Zia. General Ziaur Rahman was assassinated on May 30, 1981 at Chittagong Circuit House in a 'failed coup' orchestrated by a section of the army. He took power as chief martial law administrator on Apr 21,1977. Office secretary Rizvi Ahmed told bdnews24.com that BNP would observe the "martyrdom day" of Zia across the country with due solemnity. Party leaders and workers led by party chief Khaleda Zia would place wreath at the grave of Zia at 10 in the morning which would be followed by milad mahfil and offering prayer, he said Khaleda would distribute food among the destitute for three consecutive days since Saturday, Rizvi said Major Ziur Rahman proclaimed the war of independence from Kalurghat radio station on behalf of independence hero Sheikh Mujibur Rahman on Mar 27, 1971. Later, Zia, one of the sector commanders of Bangladesh's war of independence from Pakistan, was widely criticised for imposing military rule and rehabilitating the anti-liberation elements in politics. Zia took the charge as chief of army just after then the president Sheikh Mujibur Rahman was killed along with his family members on Aug 15, 1975 by some derailed army members. On Nov 7 the same year, he became deputy chief martial law administrator under president ASM Sayeem's government and took charge as chief martial law administrator on Apr 21, 1977. Zia was sworn in as president 